In previous sections, we have evaluated the trigonometric functions at various angles, but at times we need to know what angle would yield a specific sine, cosine, or tangent value. For this, we need inverse functions. Recall that for a one-to-one function, if \(f(a)=b\), then an inverse function would satisfy \(f^{-1} (b)=a\). You probably are already recognizing an issue – that the sine, cosine, and tangent functions are not one-to-one functions. To define an inverse of these functions, we will need to restrict the domain of these functions to yield a new function that is one-to-one. We choose a domain for each function that includes the angle zero. On these restricted domains, we can define the inverse sine, inverse cosine, and inverse tangent functions. INVERSE SINE, COSINE, AND TANGENT FUNCTIONS and their inverses For angles in the interval \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\), if \(\sin \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(\sin ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(\sin ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain [-1, 1] and range \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\) The \(\sin ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arcsine function, and notated \(\arcsin \left(aight)\). For angles in the interval \(\left[0,\pi ight]\), if \(\cos \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(\cos ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain [-1, 1] and range \(\left[0,\pi ight]\) The \(\cos ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arccosine function, and notated \(\arccos \left(aight)\). For angles in the interval \(\left(-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight)\), if \(	an \left(	heta ight)=a\), then \(	an ^{-1} \left(aight)=	heta\) \(	an ^{-1} \left(xight)\) has domain of all real numbers and range \(\left(-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight)\) The \(	an ^{-1} \left(xight)\) is sometimes called the arctangent function, and notated \(\arctan \left(aight)\). The graphs of the inverse functions are shown here: Notice that the output of each of these inverse functions is an \(angle\). Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) Evaluate \(\sin ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(	an ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-1ight)\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{2} ight)\) Answer a) \(-\dfrac{\pi }{2}\) b) \(-\dfrac{\pi }{4}\) c) \(\pi\) d) \(\dfrac{\pi }{3}\) Exercise Evaluate \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-0.4ight)\) using your calculator. Answer \[1.9823	ext{ or }113.578\mathrm{{}^\circ}
onumber\] In Section 5.5, we worked with trigonometry on a right triangle to solve for the sides of a triangle given one side and an additional angle. Using the inverse trig functions, we can solve for the angles of a right triangle given two sides. There are times when we need to compose a trigonometric function with an inverse trigonometric function. In these cases, we can find exact values for the resulting expressions Exercise \(\PageIndex{3}\) Evaluate \(\cos ^{-1} \left(\sin \left(-\dfrac{11\pi }{4} ight)ight)\). Answer \[\sin \left(-\dfrac{11\pi }{4} ight)=-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} . \cos ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} ight)=\dfrac{3\pi }{4} 
onumber\] Exercise \(\PageIndex{4}\) Evaluate \(\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)ight)\). Answer Let \(	heta =\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)\) so \[\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{7}{9}
onumber\] Using Pythagorean Identity, \(\sin ^{2} 	heta +\cos ^{2} 	heta =1\), so \[\left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)^{2} +\cos ^{2} 	heta =1
onumber\] Solving, \[\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{9} ight)ight)=\cos \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{4\sqrt{2} }{9}
onumber\] We can also find compositions involving algebraic expressions Exercise \(\PageIndex{5}\) Find a simplified expression for \(\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)ight)\), for \(-\dfrac{1}{4} \le x\le \dfrac{1}{4}\). Answer Let \(	heta =	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)\), so \(	an (	heta )=4x\). We can represent this on a triangle as \(	an (	heta )=\dfrac{4x}{1}\). The hypotenuse of the triangle would be \(\sqrt{\left(4xight)^{2} +1}\). \[\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(4xight)ight)=\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{4x}{\sqrt{16x^{2} +1} }
onumber\] Important Topics of This Section Inverse trig functions: arcsine, arccosine and arctangent Domain restrictions Evaluating inverses using unit circle values and the calculator Simplifying numerical expressions involving the inverse trig functions Simplifying algebraic expressions involving the inverse trig functions

examples.text:
Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) Evaluate \(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{2} ight)\) \(\sin ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} ight)\) \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)\) \(	an ^{-1} \left(1ight)\) Solution a) Evaluating \(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{2} ight)\) is the same as asking what angle would have a sine value of \(\dfrac{1}{2}\). In other words, what angle \(	heta\) would satisfy \(\sin \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{1}{2}\)? There are multiple angles that would satisfy this relationship, such as \(\dfrac{\pi }{6}\) and \(\dfrac{5\pi }{6}\), but we know we need the angle in the range of \(\sin ^{-1} \left(xight)\), the interval \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\), so the answer will be \[\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{1}{2} ight)=\dfrac{\pi }{6}
onumber\] Remember that the inverse is a function so for each input, we will get exactly one output. b) Evaluating \(\sin ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} ight)\), we know that \(\dfrac{5\pi }{4}\) and \(\dfrac{7\pi }{4}\) both have a sine value of \(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}\), but neither is in the interval \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\). For that, we need the negative angle coterminal with \(\dfrac{7\pi }{4}\). \[\sin ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} ight)=-\dfrac{\pi }{4}
onumber\] c) Evaluating \(\cos ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)\), we are looking for an angle in the interval \(\left[0,\pi ight]\) with a cosine value of \(-\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}\). The angle that satisfies this is \[\cos ^{-1} \left(-\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)=\dfrac{5\pi }{6}
onumber\] d) Evaluating \(	an ^{-1} \left(1ight)\), we are looking for an angle in the interval \(\left(-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight)\) with a tangent value of 1. The correct angle is \[	an ^{-1} \left(1ight)=\dfrac{\pi }{4}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Solve the triangle for the angle \(	heta\). Solution Since we know the hypotenuse and the side adjacent to the angle, it makes sense for us to use the cosine function. \[\cos \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{9}{12}
onumber\]Using the definition of the inverse, \[	heta =\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{9}{12} ight)
onumber\]Evaluating \[	heta \approx 0.7227	ext{, or about }41.4096\mathrm{{}^\circ}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{5}\) Find an exact value for \(\sin \left(\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{4}{5} ight)ight)\). Solution Beginning with the inside, we can say there is some angle so \(	heta =\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{4}{5} ight)\), which means \(\cos \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{4}{5}\), and we are looking for \(\sin \left(	heta ight)\). We can use the Pythagorean identity to do this. \[\sin ^{2} \left(	heta ight)+\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)=1
onumber\]Using our known value for cosine \[\sin ^{2} \left(	heta ight)+\left(\dfrac{4}{5} ight)^{2} =1
onumber\]Solving for sine \[\sin ^{2} \left(	heta ight)=1-\dfrac{16}{25}
onumber\] \[\sin \left(	heta ight)=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{9}{25} } =\pm \dfrac{3}{5}
onumber\] Since we know that the inverse cosine always gives an angle on the interval \(\left[0,\pi ight]\), we know that the sine of that angle must be positive, so \[\sin \left(\cos ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{4}{5} ight)ight)=\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{3}{5}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{6}\) Find an exact value for \(\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{4} ight)ight)\). Solution While we could use a similar te chnique as in the last example, we will demonstrate a different technique here. From the inside, we know there is an angle so \(	an \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{7}{4}\). We can envision this as the opposite and adjacent sides on a right triangle. Using the Pythagorean Theorem, we can find the hypotenuse of this triangle: \[4^{2} +7^{2} =hypotenuse ^{2}
onumber\] \[hypotenuse=\sqrt{65}
onumber\] Now, we can represent the sine of the angle as opposite side divided by hypotenuse. \[\sin \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{7}{\sqrt{65} }
onumber\] This gives us our desired composition \[\sin \left(	an ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{7}{4} ight)ight)=\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{7}{\sqrt{65} } .
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{7}\) Find a simplified expression for \(\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{x}{3} ight)ight)\), for \(-3\le x\le 3\). Solution We know there is an angle \(	heta\) so that \(\sin \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{x}{3}\). Using the Pythagorean Theorem, \[\sin ^{2} \left(	heta ight)+\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)=1
onumber\]Using our known expression for sine \[\left(\dfrac{x}{3} ight)^{2} +\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)=1
onumber\]Solving for cosine \[\cos ^{2} \left(	heta ight)=1-\dfrac{x^{2} }{9}
onumber\] \[\cos \left(	heta ight)=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{9-x^{2} }{9} } =\pm \dfrac{\sqrt{9-x^{2} } }{3}
onumber\] Since we know that the inverse sine must give an angle on the interval \(\left[-\dfrac{\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{\pi }{2} ight]\), we can deduce that the cosine of that angle must be positive. This gives us \[\cos \left(\sin ^{-1} \left(\dfrac{x}{3} ight)ight)=\dfrac{\sqrt{9-x^{2} } }{3}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{2}\) A circle of radius \(5\sqrt{2}\) intersects the line \(x = -5\) at two points. Find the angles \(	heta\) on the interval \(0 \le 	heta <2\pi\), where the circle and line intersect. Solution The \(x\) coordinate of a point on a circle can be found as \(x=r\cos \left(	heta ight)\), so the \(x\) coordinate of points on this circle would be \(x=5\sqrt{2} \cos \left(	heta ight)\). To find where the line \(x = -5\) intersects the circle, we can solve for where the \(x\) value on the circle would be -5. \[-5=5\sqrt{2} \cos \left(	heta ight)
onumber\]Isolating the cosine \[\dfrac{-1}{\sqrt{2} } =\cos \left(	heta ight)
onumber\] Recall that \(\dfrac{-1}{\sqrt{2} } =\dfrac{-\sqrt{2} }{2}\), so we are solving \[\cos \left(	heta ight)=\dfrac{-\sqrt{2} }{2}
onumber\] We can recognize this as one of our special cosine values from our unit circle, and it corresponds with angles \[	heta =\dfrac{3\pi }{4}	ext{ and }	heta =\dfrac{5\pi }{4}
onumber\]

