In the last chapter, we solved basic trigonometric equations. In this section, we explore the techniques needed to solve more complicated trig equations. Building from what we already know makes this a much easier task. Consider the function \(f(x)=2x^{2} +x\). If you were asked to solve \(f(x)=0\), it requires simple algebra: \[2x^{2} +x=0
onumber\]Factor \[x(2x+1)=0
onumber\]Giving solutions \[x = 0	ext{ or }x = -\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] Similarly, for \(g(t)=\sin (t)\), if we asked you to solve \(g(t)=0\), you can solve this using unit circle values: \[\sin (t)=0	ext{ for }t=0, \pi , 2\pi	ext{ and so on.}
onumber\] Using these same concepts, we consider the composition of these two functions: \[f(g(t))=2(\sin (t))^{2} +(\sin (t))=2\sin ^{2} (t)+\sin (t)
onumber\] This creates an equation that is a polynomial trig function. With these types of functions, we use algebraic techniques like factoring and the quadratic formula, along with trigonometric identities and techniques, to solve equations. As a reminder, here are some of the essential trigonometric identities that we have learned so far: Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) Solve \(2\sin ^{2} (t)+3\sin (t)+1=0\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Answer Factor as \[\left(2\sin (t)+1ight)\left(\sin (t)+1ight)=0
onumber\] \[2\sin (t)+1=0	ext{ at }t=\dfrac{7\pi }{6} ,\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] \[\sin (t)+1=0	ext{ at }t=\dfrac{3\pi }{2}
onumber\] \[t=\dfrac{7\pi }{6} ,\dfrac{3\pi }{2} ,\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] When solving some trigonometric equations, it becomes necessary to first rewrite the equation using trigonometric identities. One of the most common is the Pythagorean Identity, \(\sin ^{2} (	heta )+\cos ^{2} (	heta )=1\) which allows you to rewrite \(\sin ^{2} (	heta )\) in terms of \(\cos ^{2} (	heta )\) or vice versa, IDENTITIES Alternate Forms of the Pythagorean Identity \[ egin{array}{l} {\sin ^{2} (	heta )=1-\cos ^{2} (	heta )} \ {\cos ^{2} (	heta )=1-\sin ^{2} (	heta )} \end{array}\] These identities become very useful whenever an equation involves a combination of sine and cosine functions. Exercise \(\PageIndex{3}\) Solve \(2\sin ^{2} (t)=3\cos (t)\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Answer \[2\left(1-\cos ^{2} (t)ight)=3\cos (t)
onumber\] \[2\cos ^{2} (t)+3\cos (t)-2=0
onumber\] \[\left(2\cos (t)-1ight)\left(\cos (t)+2ight)=0
onumber\] \(\cos (t)+2=0\) has no solutions \(2\cos (t)-1=0\) at \(t=\dfrac{\pi }{3} ,\dfrac{5\pi }{3}\) In addition to the Pythagorean Identity, it is often necessary to rewrite the tangent, secant, cosecant, and cotangent as part of solving an equation. Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Solve \(\sec (	heta )=2\cos (	heta )\) to find the first four positive solutions. Answer \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (	heta )} =2\cos (	heta )
onumber\] \[\dfrac{1}{2} =\cos ^{2} (	heta )
onumber\] \[\cos (	heta )=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{1}{2} } =\pm \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}
onumber\] \[	heta =\dfrac{\pi }{4} ,\dfrac{3\pi }{4} ,\dfrac{5\pi }{4} ,\dfrac{7\pi }{4}
onumber\] Important Topics of This Section Review of Trig Identities Solving Trig Equations By Factoring Using the Quadratic Formula Utilizing Trig Identities to simplify

examples.text:
Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) Solve \(2\sin ^{2} (t)+\sin (t)=0\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Solution This equation kind of looks like a quadratic equation, but with sin( t ) in place of an algebraic variable (we often call such an equation “quadratic in sine”). As with all quadratic equations, we can use factoring techniques or the quadratic formula. This expression factors nicely, so we proceed by factoring out the common factor of sin(\(t\)): \[\sin (t)\left(2\sin (t)+1ight)=0
onumber\] Using the zero product theorem, we know that the product on the left will equal zero if either factor is zero, allowing us to break this equation into two cases: \[\sin (t)=0	ext{ or }2\sin (t)+1=0
onumber\] We can solve each of these equations independently, using our knowledge of special angles. \[\sin (t)=0
onumber\] \[2\sin (t)+1=0
onumber\] \[t = 0	ext{ or }t = \pi
onumber\] \[\sin (t)=-\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] \[t=\dfrac{7\pi }{6}	ext{ or }t=\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] Together, this gives us four solutions to the equation on \(0\le t<2\pi\): \[t=0,\pi ,\dfrac{7\pi }{6} ,\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] We could check these answers are reasonable by graphing the function and comparing the zeros.

Example \(\PageIndex{2}\) Solve \(3\sec ^{2} (t)-5\sec (t)-2=0\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Solution Since the left side of this equation is quadratic in secant, we can try to factor it, and hope it factors nicely. If it is easier to for you to consider factoring without the trig function present, consider using a substitution \(u=\sec (t)\), resulting in \(3u^{2} -5u-2=0\), and then try to factor: \[3u^{2} -5u-2=(3u+1)(u-2)
onumber\] Undoing the substitution, \[(3\sec (t)+1)(\sec (t)-2)=0
onumber\] Since we have a product equal to zero, we break it into the two cases and solve each separately. \[3\sec (t)+1=0
onumber\]Isolate the secant \[\sec (t)=-\dfrac{1}{3}
onumber\]Rewrite as a cosine \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (t)} =-\dfrac{1}{3}
onumber\]Invert both sides \[\cos (t)=-3
onumber\] Since the cosine has a range of [-1, 1], the cosine will never take on an output of -3. There are no solutions to this case. Continuing with the second case, \[\sec (t)-2=0
onumber\]Isolate the secant \[\sec (t)=2
onumber\]Rewrite as a cosine \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (t)} =2
onumber\]Invert both sides \[\cos (t)=\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\]This gives two solutions \[t=\dfrac{\pi }{3}	ext{ or }t=\dfrac{5\pi }{3}
onumber\] These are the only two solutions on the interval. By utilizing technology to graph \(f(t)=3\sec ^{2} (t)-5\sec (t)-2\), a look at a graph confirms there are only two zeros for this function on the interval [0, 2 \(\pi\)), which assures us that we didn’t miss anything.

