onumber\] Since the double angle for sine involves both sine and cosine, we’ll need to first find \(\cos (	heta )\), which we can do using the Pythagorean Identity. \[\sin ^{2} (	heta )+\cos ^{2} (	heta )=1
onumber\] \[\left(\dfrac{3}{5} ight)^{2} +\cos ^{2} (	heta )=1
onumber\] \[\cos ^{2} (	heta )=1-\dfrac{9}{25}
onumber\] \[\cos (	heta )=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{16}{25} } =\pm \dfrac{4}{5}
onumber\] Since \(	heta\) is in the second quadrant, we know that cos( \(	heta\) ) \(\mathrm{<}\) 0, so \[\cos (	heta )=-\dfrac{4}{5}
onumber\] Now we can evaluate the sine double angle \[\sin (2	heta )=2\sin (	heta )\cos (	heta )=2\left(\dfrac{3}{5} ight)\left(-\dfrac{4}{5} ight)=-\dfrac{24}{25}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Simplify \(\dfrac{\cos (2t)}{\cos (t)-\sin (t)}\). Solution With three choices for how to rewrite the double angle, we need to consider which will be the most useful. To simplify this expression, it would be great if the denominator would cancel with something in the numerator, which would require a factor of \(\cos (t)-\sin (t)\) in the numerator, which is most likely to occur if we rewrite the numerator with a mix of sine and cosine. \[\dfrac{\cos (2t)}{\cos (t)-\sin (t)}
onumber\]Apply the double angle identity \[=\dfrac{\cos ^{2} (t)-\sin ^{2} (t)}{\cos (t)-\sin (t)}
onumber\]Factor the numerator \[=\dfrac{\left(\cos (t)-\sin (t)ight)\left(\cos (t)+\sin (t)ight)}{\cos (t)-\sin (t)}
onumber\]Cancelling the common factor \[=\cos (t)+\sin (t)
onumber\]Resulting in the most simplified form

Example \(\PageIndex{4}\) Prove \(\sec (2\alpha )=\dfrac{\sec ^{2} (\alpha )}{2-\sec ^{2} (\alpha )}\). Solution Since the right side seems a bit more complicated than the left side, we begin there. \[\dfrac{\sec ^{2} (\alpha )}{2-\sec ^{2} (\alpha )}
onumber\]Rewrite the secants in terms of cosine \[=\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} }{2-\dfrac{1}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} }
onumber\] At this point, we could rewrite the bottom with common denominators, subtract the terms, invert and multiply, then simplify. Alternatively, we can multiple both the top and bottom by \(\cos ^{2} (\alpha )\), the common denominator: \[=\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} \cdot \cos ^{2} (\alpha )}{\left(2-\dfrac{1}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} ight)\cdot \cos ^{2} (\alpha )}
onumber\]Distribute on the bottom \[=\dfrac{\dfrac{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} }{2\cos ^{2} (\alpha )-\dfrac{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )}{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )} \cdot }
onumber\]Simplify \[=\dfrac{1}{2\cos ^{2} (\alpha )-1}
onumber\]Rewrite the denominator as a double angle \[=\dfrac{1}{\cos (2\alpha )}
onumber\]Rewrite as a secant \[=\sec (2\alpha )
onumber\]Establishing the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{7}\) Rewrite \(\cos ^{4} (x)\) without any powers. Solution \[\cos ^{4} (x)=\left(\cos ^{2} (x)ight)^{2}
onumber\]Using the power reduction formula \[=\left(\dfrac{\cos (2x)+1}{2} ight)^{2}
onumber\]Square the numerator and denominator \[=\dfrac{\left(\cos (2x)+1ight)^{2} }{4}
onumber\]Expand the numerator \[=\dfrac{\cos ^{2} (2x)+2\cos (2x)+1}{4}
onumber\]Split apart the fraction \[=\dfrac{\cos ^{2} (2x)}{4} +\dfrac{2\cos (2x)}{4} +\dfrac{1}{4}
onumber\]Apply the formula above to \(\cos ^{2} (2x)\) \[\cos ^{2} (2x)=\dfrac{\cos (2\cdot 2x)+1}{2}
onumber\] \[=\dfrac{\left(\dfrac{\cos (4x)+1}{2} ight)}{4} +\dfrac{2\cos (2x)}{4} +\dfrac{1}{4}
onumber\]Simplify \[=\dfrac{\cos (4x)}{8} +\dfrac{1}{8} +\dfrac{1}{2} \cos (2x)+\dfrac{1}{4}
onumber\]Combine the constants \[=\dfrac{\cos (4x)}{8} +\dfrac{1}{2} \cos (2x)+\dfrac{3}{8}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{8}\) Find an exact value for \(\cos \left(15{}^\circ ight)\). Solution Since 15 degrees is half of 30 degrees, we can use our result from above: \[\cos (15{}^\circ )=\cos \left(\dfrac{30{}^\circ }{2} ight)=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{\cos (30{}^\circ )+1}{2} }
onumber\] We can evaluate the cosine. Since 15 degrees is in the first quadrant, we need the positive result. \[\sqrt{\dfrac{\cos (30{}^\circ )+1}{2} } =\sqrt{\dfrac{\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} +1}{2} }
onumber\] \[=\sqrt{\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{4} +\dfrac{1}{2} }
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) A population of elk currently averages 2000 elk, and that average has been growing by 4% each year. Due to seasonal fluctuation, the population oscillates from 50 below average in the winter up to 50 above average in the summer. Find a function that models the number of elk after \(t\) years, starting in the winter. Solution There are two components to the behavior of the elk population: the changing average, and the oscillation. The average is an exponential growth, starting at 2000 and growing by 4% each year. Writing a formula for this: \[average=initial(1+r)^{t} =2000(1+0.04)^{t}
onumber\] For the oscillation, since the population oscillates 50 above and below average, the amplitude will be 50. Since it takes one year for the population to cycle, the period is 1. We find the value of the horizontal stretch coefficient \[B= rac{	ext{original period}}{	ext{new period}}= rac{2\pi }{1}=2\pi 
onumber\] The function starts in winter, so the shape of the function will be a negative cosine, since it starts at the lowest value. Putting it all together, the equation would be: \[P(t)=-50\cos (2\pi {\kern 1pt} t)+midline
onumber\] Since the midline represents the average population, we substitute in the exponential function into the population equation to find our final equation: \[P(t)=-50\cos (2\pi {\kern 1pt} t)+2000(1+0.04)^{t}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{5}\) A spring with natural length of 30 cm is pulled out 10 cm and released. It oscillates 4 times per second. After 2 seconds, the amplitude has decreased to 5 cm. Find a function that models the position of the spring. Solution The oscillation has a period of \(\dfrac{1}{4}\) second, so \(B = \dfrac{2\pi}{1/4} = 8\pi\). Since the spring will oscillate on either side of the natural length, the midline will be at 30 cm. It begins at the furthest distance from the wall, suggesting a cosine model. Together, this gives \[f(t)=A(t)\cos (8\pi {\kern 1pt} t)+30.
onumber\] For the amplitude function, we notice that the amplitude starts at 10 cm, and decreases to 5 cm after 2 seconds. This gives two points (0, 10) and (2, 5) that must be satisfied by an exponential function: \(A(0)=10\) and \(A(2)=5\). Since the function is exponential, we can use the form \(A(t)=ab^{t}\). Substituting the first point, \(10=ab^{0}\), so \(a = 10\). Substituting in the second point, \[5=10b^{2}
onumber\]Divide by 10 \[\dfrac{1}{2} =b^{2}
onumber\]Take the square root \[b=\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{2} } \approx 0.707
onumber\] This gives an amplitude function of \(A(t)=10(0.707)^{t}\). Combining this with the oscillation, \[f(t)=10(0.707)^{t} \cos (8\pi t)+30
onumber\]

